<div class="comment-content"><b>Prerequisites (minimal)</b><br /><br />This text rests on six well-established ideas:<br /><br /><ol><br /><li><b>Solomonoff induction</b> — The optimal way to infer future behavior from observations is to assign higher probability to the <i>shortest program</i> (in bits) that explains the data so far.<br><br />(<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solomonoff%27s_theory_of_inductive_inference">Ray Solomonoff, 1964</a>; Wikipedia: Solomonoff's theory of inductive inference)</li><br /><br /><li><b>Kolmogorov complexity</b> — The complexity of any object (including a sequence of human actions) is the length of the shortest computer program that outputs it. Real human behavior has extremely high, largely incompressible Kolmogorov complexity.<br><br />(<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kolmogorov_complexity">Andrey Kolmogorov, 1963</a>; Wikipedia: Kolmogorov complexity)</li><br /><br /><li><b>Decentralized control</b> — Complex coordination (e.g., the Internet) emerges from local rules without any central node holding the full map (TCP/IP packet switching is the canonical example).<br><br />(Standard networking; Hayek’s spontaneous order is the economic analogue)</li><br /><br /><li><b>Economic calculation problem</b> — Rational allocation of scarce resources is possible for an individual (or a society) only when stable prices exist in a conserved medium of exchange. Without it, computation collapses.<br><br />(<a href="https://mises.org/library/economic-calculation-socialist-commonwealth">Ludwig von Mises, “Economic Calculation in the Socialist Commonwealth”, 1920</a>)</li><br /><br /><li><b>Bounded individual complexity + inductive-inference bottleneck</b> — Any single person has strictly limited algorithmic capacity. Person-to-person reports are always lossy projections; they cannot be fully trusted because the receiver must inductively guess the hidden “source code” behind the observed signal (replay attacks, incentives, noise).</li><br /><br /><li><b>Core observation</b> — Tasks whose Kolmogorov complexity exceeds any single brain can be solved only by decentralized markets running on <i>physically preserving / conserved money</i> (gold, Bitcoin-as-energy, etc.). Fiat or changeable “reports” inject central rewriting rules that cap complexity and destroy reliable calculation.<br><br />(Synthesis of the above; cf. Elon Musk: “Bitcoin is based on energy — you can issue fake fiat currency, but it is impossible to fake energy”)</li><br /></ol><br /><br />With these six concepts alone, the rest of the argument follows directly: elementary action triangles (actor–means–ends) compose into unbounded market computation, while any central “interpreter” or regulator necessarily fails.<div class='edittime'><em>Edited <span class="datetime"><span class="comment-date-text">Date: </span> <span title="">2026-03-24 07:15 am (UTC)</span></span></em></div></div></div>
</div>
